{"key":"post-13740706","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>13740706</id>\n<content>Correct, rhizomorphic mycelium is vastly over rated.&amp;nbsp; It's something we tend to isolate in species which form it, but there's no guarantee that a perfectly rhizomorphic mycelium on a petri dish will remain that way when it goes to grains, or that it will be a particularly good fruiter.&amp;nbsp; It's related far more to nutrient load than genetics, with a nutrient poor substrate more likely to develop rhizomorphs.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;When doing strain isolation, it's important to grab enough strains so that you can test them all to find a good fruiting strain.&amp;nbsp; When growers isolate a single rhizomorphic strain and then toss out all the others, they rarely end up with a good one.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>13750882</next>\n<prev>13739946</prev>\n<first>13737786</first>\n<last>13750882</last>\n<when>1294339324</when>\n<utime>01/06/11 08:42 PM</utime>\n</post>"}